      "so `g` is decreasing.\n3. Check that for `x ∈ (e^{-1/2}, 1)`, `g'(x) > 0`, so `g` is increasing.\n4. Deduce that `g(x)` has a minimum at `x = e^{-1/2}`.\n\nHowever, perhaps there is already in Lean a lemma that a continuous function on a compact interval attains its bounds, and perhaps `(0, 1]` can be handled as `[ε, 1]` with `ε → 0^+`.\n\nBut perhaps not, and we need to be more explicit.\n\nAlternatively, in Lean, perhaps we do not even need the exact bound of `1/(2e)` but can be more wasteful and simply note that for `x ∈ (0, 1]`, we have `x² ≤ 1`, `|log x| ≤ 1` when `x ≥ 1/e`, and when `x < 1/e`, `x² log x > -x`. \n\nIndeed, for `x ∈ (0, 1/e)`, `log x < -1`, and thus `x² log x < -x² < 0`, but also `x² log x > -x`, because `x log x > -1` for `x ∈ (0, 1)` (since `x log x → 0` as `x → 0+`, and its derivative is `log x + 1`, which is negative for `x ∈ (0, 1/e)` and positive for `x ∈ (1/e, 1)`). \n\nAlternatively, a better approach is:\n1. Note that `x² log x → 0` as `x → 0+`.\n2. Deduce that there exists a constant `C` such that `x² log x ≥ -C` for all `x ∈ (0, 1]`. \n\nActually, this is trivial, since as `x ∈ (0, 1]`, `x² log x ≥ -1`: indeed, `x² ≤ 1` and `log x ≥ -1` for `x ≥ 1/e`, and for `x ∈ (0, 1/e)`, `log x < -1`, but `x² log x > -x² > -1`. \n\nBut actually `x² log x` has a minimum of `-1/(2e)`, so we can simply use `C = 1`. \n\nIndeed,",
      "\n  have h₁ : (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)).hasFiniteMass := by\n    rw [MeasureTheory.finite_mass_iff]\n    <;> simp [volume_Ioc]\n    <;> norm_num\n  refine' MeasureTheory.hasFiniteIntegral_of_hasFiniteMass_of_ae_stronglyMeasurable _\n  <;> aesop",
      "\n    <;> try norm_num\n    <;> try linarith\n  exact h₂",
      "have that",
      "\n  have h₁ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)) := by\n    have h₂ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := Φ₅_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n    have h₃ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)) := by\n      -- Use the fact that a continuous function on a compact set is integrable\n      have h₄ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := Φ₅_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n      have h₅ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)) := by\n        -- Use the fact that the integral of a continuous function on a compact interval is finite\n        refine' (continuousOn_iff_continuous_restrict.mp h₄).hasFiniteIntegral_Ioc\n        <;> norm_num\n        <;> linarith\n      exact h₅\n    exact h₃\n  exact h₁",
      "\n  have h₁ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n    -- Prove that the integral is bounded on the interval (0, 1]\n    have h₂ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Icc 0 1) := by\n      -- Show that Φ₅ is continuous on [0, 1]\n      have h₃ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Ioc 0 1) := Φ₅_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n      have h₄ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) ({0} : Set ℝ) := by\n        -- Check the continuity at x = 0\n        have h₅ : ContinuousAt (Φ₅ r) 0 := by\n          -- Use the fact that Φ₅ is defined to be 0 at x = 0\n          have h₆ : (Φ₅ r) 0 = 0 := by\n            simp [Φ₅]\n            <;>\n            ring_nf\n            <;>\n            norm_num\n          have h₇ : ContinuousAt (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₅ r) x) 0 := by\n            -- Prove continuity at 0\n            have h₈ : ContinuousAt (fun x : ℝ => (r * x) ^ 4 * (r * x - 1) ^ 2 * x ^ 3) 0 := by\n              -- Prove that the polynomial part is continuous\n              continuity\n            have h₉ : ContinuousAt (fun x : ℝ => if x = 0 then 0 else (r * x) ^ 4 * (r * x - 1) ^ 2 * x ^ 3) 0 := by\n              -- Prove continuity of the piecewise function at 0\n              have h₁₀ : (if (0 : ℝ) = 0 then 0 else (r * (0 : ℝ)) ^ 4 * (r * (0 : ℝ) - 1) ^ 2 * (0 : ℝ) ^ 3) = 0 := by\n                simp\n              have h₁₁ : ContinuousAt (fun x : ℝ => (r * x) ^ 4 * (r * x - 1) ^ 2 * x ^ 3) 0 := by\n                continuity\n              -- Use the fact that the function is equal to the polynomial except at 0\n              convert h₁₁.tendsto.congr' _ using 1\n              <;> simp_all [h₁₀]\n              <;> aesop\n            simpa [Φ₅] using h₉\n          exact h₇\n        -- Use the fact that continuity at a point implies continuity on a singleton set\n        exact ContinuousAt.continuousOn h₅\n      -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0, 1]\n      have h₅ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Icc 0 1) := by\n        apply ContinuousOn.mono _ (by\n          -- Show that [0, 1] is a subset of [0, 1] ∪ (0, 1]\n          have h₆ : (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) ⊆ (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) := by\n            intro x hx\n            exact hx\n          have h₇ : (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) ⊆ (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) := by\n            intro x hx\n            exact hx\n          -- Combine the intervals\n          have h₈ : (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) ⊆ (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) := by\n            intro x hx\n            exact hx\n          -- Use the fact that the intervals are subsets of each other\n          have h₉ : (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) ⊆ (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) := by\n            intro x hx\n            exact hx\n          -- Combine all the subsets to get the final result\n          have h₁₀ : (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) ⊆ (Icc 0 1 : Set ℝ) := by\n            intro x hx\n            exact hx\n          exact h₁₀\n        )\n        -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on (0, 1] and {0}\n        have h₆ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Ioc 0 1) := Φ₅_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n        have h₇ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) ({0} : Set ℝ) := h₄\n        -- Combine the continuity on the intervals\n        have h₈ : ContinuousOn (Φ₅ r) (Ioc 0 1 ∪ ({0} : Set ℝ)) := ContinuousOn.union h₆ h₇\n        -- Show that (0, 1] ∪ {0} = [0, 1]\n        have h₉ : (Ioc 0 1 ∪ ({0} : Set ℝ)) = Set.Icc 0 1 := by\n          ext x\n          simp [Ioc, Icc, le_of_lt]\n          <;>\n          by_cases h : x = 0 <;>\n          by_cases h' : x < 1 <;>\n          by_cases h'' : 0 < x <;>\n          simp_all [lt_irrefl]\n          <;>\n          (try { nlinarith }) <;>\n          (try { linarith }) <;>\n          (try { nlinarith }) <;>\n          (try { linarith })\n          <;>\n          (try {\n            cases' lt_or_le x 0 with h''' h'''\n            · simp_all [lt_irrefl]\n              <;> nlinarith\n            · simp_all [lt_irrefl]\n              <;> nlinarith\n          })\n        -- Use the fact that the union of the intervals is [0, 1]\n        rw [h₉] at h₈\n        exact h₈\n      exact h₅\n    -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0, 1] to prove it is bounded\n    have h₃ : BoundedOn (Φ₅ r) (Icc 0 1) := by\n      -- Use the fact that continuous functions on compact sets are bounded\n      apply IsCompact.boundedOn_image\n      · exact isCompact_Icc\n      · exact h₂\n    -- Use the fact that the function is bounded to prove that the integral is finite\n    have h₄ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n      -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0, 1] to prove it is bounded\n      have h₅ : BoundedOn (Φ₅ r) (Icc 0 1) := h₃\n      -- Use the fact that the function is bounded to prove that the integral is finite\n      have h₆ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n        -- Use the fact that the function is bounded to prove that the integral is finite\n        refine' (hasFiniteIntegral_of_boundedOn_of_hasFiniteMeasure _\n          (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)).hasFiniteMeasure).mpr _\n        · -- Prove that the function is bounded on the interval (0, 1]\n          refine' BoundedOn.mono _ (Set.Ioc_subset_Icc_self)\n          exact h₅\n        · -- Prove that the set (0, 1] has finite measure\n          simp [volume_Ioc]\n          <;>\n          norm_num\n          <;>\n          linarith\n      exact h₆\n    exact h₄\n  -- Use the fact that the integral is finite to prove that the function is integrable on (0, 1]\n  have h₂ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := h₁\n  have h₃ : IntegrableOn (Φ₅ r) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) volume := by\n    -- Use the fact that the integral is finite to prove that the function is integrable on (0, 1]\n    have h₄ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₅ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := h₂\n    -- Use the fact that the integral is finite to prove that the function is integrable on (0, 1]\n    exact h₄.integrableOn\n  exact h₃",
      "\n  sorry",
      "\n  refine' (hasFiniteIntegral_of_boundedOn_restrict_of_ae_stronglyMeasurable _ _)\n  · -- Show that the function is bounded on [0,1]\n    have h₁ : BddAbove (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₅ r) x)) := by\n      use (3 : ℝ)\n      intro y\n      rcases y with ⟨x, rfl⟩\n      have h₂ : (Φ₅ r x) ≤ 3 := by\n        -- Use the fact that Φ₅ is bounded above by 3 on [0,1]\n        have h₃ : 0 ≤ x := by linarith [hr]\n        have h₄ : x ≤ 1 := by\n          -- Prove that x is within the interval [0,1]\n          have h₅ : x ∈ Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 := by\n            -- x is in the interval (0,1]\n            exact by\n              simp_all [Φ₅]\n              <;>\n              (try norm_num) <;>\n              (try linarith) <;>\n              (try\n                {\n                  aesop\n                }) <;>\n              (try\n                {\n                  simp_all [Ioc, Icc]\n                  <;>\n                  linarith\n                })\n          -- Extract the upper bound from the interval\n          exact by\n            simp_all [Ioc]\n            <;>\n            linarith\n        -- Calculate the bound\n        simp [Φ₅] at h₃ h₄ ⊢\n        <;>\n        (try norm_num at h₃ h₄ ⊢) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            cases' le_or_lt 0 (r - 1) with h₆ h₆ <;>\n            cases' le_or_lt 0 (r + 1) with h₇ h₇ <;>\n            simp_all [abs_of_nonneg, abs_of_neg, le_of_lt] <;>\n            nlinarith [sq_nonneg (x - 1), sq_nonneg (x + 1)]\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            nlinarith [sq_nonneg (x - 1), sq_nonneg (x + 1)]\n          })\n      -- Use the bound to prove the statement\n      linarith\n    have h₂ : BddBelow (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₅ r) x)) := by\n      use (-(3 : ℝ))\n      intro y\n      rcases y with ⟨x, rfl⟩\n      have h₃ : (Φ₅ r x) ≥ -3 := by\n        -- Use the fact that Φ₅ is bounded below by -3 on [0,1]\n        have h₄ : 0 ≤ x := by linarith [hr]\n        have h₅ : x ≤ 1 := by\n          -- Prove that x is within the interval [0,1]\n          have h₆ : x ∈ Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 := by\n            -- x is in the interval (0,1]\n            exact by\n              simp_all [Φ₅]\n              <;>\n              (try norm_num) <;>\n              (try linarith) <;>\n              (try\n                {\n                  aesop\n                }) <;>\n              (try\n                {\n                  simp_all [Ioc, Icc]\n                  <;>\n                  linarith\n                })\n          -- Extract the upper bound from the interval\n          exact by\n            simp_all [Ioc]\n            <;>\n            linarith\n        -- Calculate the bound\n        simp [Φ₅] at h₄ h₅ ⊢\n        <;>\n        (try norm_num at h₄ h₅ ⊢) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            cases' le_or_lt 0 (r - 1) with h₆ h₆ <;>\n            cases' le_or_lt 0 (r + 1) with h₇ h₇ <;>\n            simp_all [abs_of_nonneg, abs_of_neg, le_of_lt] <;>\n            nlinarith [sq_nonneg (x - 1), sq_nonneg (x + 1)]\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            nlinarith [sq_nonneg (x - 1), sq_nonneg (x + 1)]\n          })\n      -- Use the bound to prove the statement\n      linarith\n    -- Conclude that the function is bounded on [0,1]\n    exact by\n      simpa using IsBounded (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₅ r) x)\n  · -- Show that the function is almost everywhere strongly measurable\n    exact ContinuousOn.aestronglyMeasurable Φ₅_contDiffOn.continuousOn",
